Government infrastructure investment programs are classic democratic policies and are strongly opposed by the Tea Party wing of the Republican Party, which is critical of the government.
So Trump could still have party-wide discussions.
The differences between energy and climate policy are more apparent.
Trump wants to build coal plants and start coal mining in the US again.
The Commission is also proposing to make oil extraction possible in protected areas, and to abrogate the Paris Agreement on Climate Change.
Clinton, on the other hand, wants to expand renewable energy in her investment program, and says: "One country will become the clean energy superpower and create millions of jobs".
"It's going to be either China or Germany or America - I want us to be".
But not only in infrastructure - international trade agreements are not too far apart.
TPP, the Transpacific Trade Agreement, both of them don't want to sign.
At the same time, both sides do not want to isolate the US from international trade - they simply want to protect American jobs better.
The Commission is also proposing to increase the amount of money that can be spent on the environment.
The current minimum wage of $7.25 is a starvation wage.
She wants to raise it to $15 an hour.
