Flight: "Every refugee woman has experienced sexual violence"
Sexual violence is almost a daily occurrence for women who flee alone.
When they arrive in Germany, they are often traumatized.
A house is a shelter.
In a large kitchen, four women are sitting.
Each one has a baby, one year old at most.
One of them was carrying her little boy.
He looks curiously into the room with wide eyes.
His mother stares at the table.
Until she realizes she's being watched.
She smiles and kisses the little one.
The scene seems normal.
Until you talk to Katrin Bahr.
She is the area manager of Condrobs, a provider of social assistance in Bavaria, and deals with the issue of women on the run.
The four women in the kitchen are fugitives.
They live in the north of Munich in one of the few decentralised accommodation facilities for single migrant women and their children in Bavaria.
In January, Condrobs opened the facility together with Pro Familia and the Munich Women's Aid.
It was recently officially opened.
Sixty people live there - about 40 women and 20 children.
There are no men, not even as visitors.
The exception is a guard outside the door.
"It is no exaggeration to say that every woman who arrives here has experienced sexual violence during her escape", says Bahr.
"Men flee because of wars, political persecution, threats of torture or death, or because their families send them to Europe as bearers of hope", she says.
Women have other reasons for fleeing: "Many steal because they see no other way out".
In their homeland, they have experienced sexual violence, forced marriage, honor killings, slavery, or forced prostitution.
It drives them away.
The escape is the continuation.
"It is not uncommon for traffickers to demand sexual acts in exchange for a bottle of water", says Bahr.
And the women are alone, they're not protected by their families.
Whoever thinks that this will end once they arrive in Germany is crazy, says Bahr.
Here, too, women living alone in refugee shelters are often seen as inferior and, at worst, abused.
As a result, she estimates that about 90 percent of the women living in the shelter in the north of Munich are traumatized.
"Some of the children were not born of their own free will".
Many women are so used to not saying anything.
"Or they don't dare to speak openly about what they've experienced because the shame is too great".
Since they often cannot help themselves, more housing is needed just for them, Bahr demands.
In Bavaria, the seven regional governments are responsible for the accommodation of refugees.
When asked if they knew of a similar project in their area of responsibility as in Munich, some say no.
In the Upper Palatinate and Upper Franconia, for example, there is no such thing in government accommodation.
In Swabia alone, women refugees are not separated from men, says Karl-Heinz Meyer, a government spokesman.
In Upper Bavaria, Lower and Middle Franconia, some communal accommodation has floors or private houses for single women and their children only.
The exception is Lower Bavaria, where there are two central shelters exclusively for women.
The Committee on Women's Rights and Gender Equality in the European Parliament also calls for women to be housed separately from men.
A study published for the committee states: "It is very important that men and women are housed separately".
"A lack of privacy or the coexistence of men and women can lead to - ongoing - violence against women".
The study says that washing rooms should be separate and easily accessible to women.
The degree to which women feel this need for protection can be seen in the demand for the house in Munich.
"Since we've been around, we've had a long waiting list", says Bahr.
You could easily open a second home.
