Russia and Turkey: an "alliance of outsiders"?
It was a gesture that ended a crisis.
The leaders of Russia and Turkey met on Tuesday to shake hands and announce an official end to the eight-month war of words and economic sanctions.
But as Vladimir Putin receives his Turkish counterpart in the gilded hall of St Petersburg Palace, I cannot help feeling that Ankara wants this reconciliation most of all.
There was the handshake, yes.
But Putin's smile was narrow-lipped and he barely radiated warmth, even for his reserved circumstances.
Recep Tayyip Erdogan, on the other hand, has repeatedly spoken of his "dear friend" Putin - one report says as many as five times.
I couldn't count it anymore.
He also promised that relations with Russia would not only return to their pre-crisis level, but would even improve.
The next day, a newspaper described how Erdogan acted as if nothing bad had ever happened.
His enthusiasm seemed to suggest the opposite.
But a sustained coolness emanating from Putin showed that the Russian head of state had not forgotten anything.
The European Parliament has already been informed of the situation in Syria, and we are very pleased that the European Union has taken the initiative to respond to the crisis.
Moscow's reaction at the time was furious.
Putin accused Ankara of backstabbing Russia and said that the Russian government had not acted in accordance with the law.
The crime was even more serious, since it was committed by a supposed friend.
Rebuilding trust will be difficult, if not impossible.
Public opinion in Russia has changed since November.
For months, the state-controlled media carried out a fierce, unabated attack on Ankara.
Suddenly it seemed that the Turks were to blame for everything.
Most serious were the accusations by senior officials that Erdogan's own family had profited from the illegal oil trade in areas of Syria controlled by the so-called Islamic State.
He vehemently denied this.
But in St. Petersburg, the official message was that it was time to move on.
The only reason this meeting took place was because President Erdogan had given Mr Putin the apology he wanted to hear.
Russia could have some kind of victory.
The advantages of a ceasefire are clear to Ankara.
Erdogan needs all the friends he can get after being nearly removed from office in a failed coup last month.
Repeated terrorist attacks on Turkey have also shaken him.
But there are also economic motives.
Russian sanctions have hit Turkey hard - especially the ban on charter flights, which usually bring several million Russian tourists to the Turkish coast each year.
The number has dropped by almost 90%.
In Russia, tour operators and charter companies will be relieved when flights resume.
They're counting on a late-season Mediterranean raid.
This week, state television predicted cheaper fruits and vegetables as soon as Turkish agricultural imports are allowed again.
A report in Vedemosti put it this way: "Tourists over there, tomatoes over here".
But the visit had an added political value for Moscow.
Ankara is angry with the West, as it considers its reaction to the attempted takeover a weak response.
In addition, there is the continuing resentment over the sluggish pace of EU accession negotiations and Putin - who is eager to take advantage of the cool mood and to diminish Turkey's relationship with the West.
The Russian head of state certainly won a bonus in Ankara for calling for support for the elected state bodies after the attempted coup.
This is, of course, a matter of course for Moscow, which itself has a deep-seated fear of regime change.
The summit in this splendid palace by the sea allowed Russia and Turkey to represent, as one analyst once described to me, "an alliance of outsiders": two countries that feel rejected and mistreated by the West and are now allying.
However, despite the public reconciliation, there are still major differences between the two.
The biggest difference is Syria, where Moscow recently gave itself the role of peacemaker, but where Russia and Turkey are supporting opposing sides.
It might be significant that after nearly three hours of initial talks, both presidents testified at the press conference that they had not even touched the subject.
The Turkish president deliberately avoided answering a question about their differences, while Putin chose to emphasize them.
There is no clear consensus on where to find common ground on Syria.
But after months of open hostility - and given the potential for total disaster when NATO member Turkey shot down the Russian fighter jet - it's surely better that the two heads of state at least talk again.
