Do the smiling faces convince?
This move has wrapped Moscow in mystery.
Sergei Ivanov was for a long time one of Vladimir Putin's closest confidants, and like him, he works for the Soviet intelligence service, the KGB.
As chief of staff, he was one of the most powerful men in the country.
In a televised meeting with President Putin, both men claimed that the chief of staff was resigning at his own request.
But despite the smile for the cameras, few here are convinced of that - especially now, just before the parliamentary elections.
So, is this the result of some kind of power struggle?
No one knows that at the moment.
But the official claim - that a man once touted as a potential president would suddenly want to lead Russia's environmental policy - has been met with great skepticism.
In his remarks to Putin, quoted on the Kremlin's website, Ivanov said: "It is true that in a conversation in early 2012 I asked you to entrust me with this very complicated - one could almost say - burdensome post for four years.
As it turns out, I've been chairman of the Russian presidential administration for four years and eight months.
Ivanov took up the post in December 2011.
