Trampolining has a certain outsider charm, in part because it sounds more appropriate for the unenlightened ear for a clown school than for the Olympics.
At this point, I should admit that I'm not an expert, just a down-to-earth enthusiast.
It has the potential for humor - the cartoonish shudder of its never-ending bang - but also the grace of gymnastics and diving, the two sports that it essentially combines.
The word "trampoline" comes from the Spanish word "el trampolín", which means "jumping board".
Aspiring winners jump on a giant trampoline, shoot up to almost 30 feet in the air, and must complete a series of falling moves (twists, splits, and saltoes) before landing on their feet.
