Amid the Olympic mania, they promise a quiet, nice moment, one that's likely to be overlooked in the general turmoil.
If the raising of consciousness can only be achieved by the opening up and objectification of male athletes - as recently suggested by the male US gymnasts according to The Wall Street Journal - then Mr. Dooley is expecting his breathless new fanbase.
"A generation protesting" in Ethiopia, Long an ally of the US
Violent protests in Ethiopia
Protesters demanding political change in Ethiopia have been met with violent resistance from the government.
Witnesses say that thousands of protesters were killed in gun battles during clashes with police.
Is Ethiopia about to collapse?
In the last decade, it has been one of the most stable countries in Africa, a solid ally of the West with a fast-growing economy.
But in recent months, anti-government protests have rocked the country and spread to more and more areas.
Last week thousands of people took to the streets demanding fundamental political changes.
The government's response has been brutal, according to human rights groups.
Witnesses said police shot and killed dozens of unarmed protesters.
Circulating videos of the protests, which are believed to be from last year or earlier this year, show security officers beating young people with sticks while forcing them to make a handstand against a wall.
The head of the UN human rights office is now demanding a full investigation.
"It has always been difficult to keep this country together and it will be even more difficult in the future", said Rashid Abdi, the Horn of Africa project manager for the International Crisis Group, a research group.
Ethiopia is the most populous country in Africa after Nigeria, and its stability is appreciated by the West.
American military and intelligence agencies are working closely with the Ethiopians to combat terror threats beyond the region, particularly in Somalia.
Ethiopia's economy expanded at a remarkable rate.
Its infrastructure has improved dramatically - there's a new commuter train in the capital Addis Ababa.
The streets are generally quiet, safe and clean.
Even though Ethiopia was far from a model of democracy - human rights organizations have consistently led the way in government repression - opposition in the country was constrained, with dissidents effectively silenced.
Many were exiled or imprisoned, killed, or driven into the wilderness.
But that could change.
"When you oppress people and they have no other option but to protest, it breaks out", said Seyoum Teshome, a lecturer in central Ethiopia.
All the youth are protesting.
A generation of protesting people.
There are numerous complaints covering everything from land use to the stranglehold on power of the ruling coalition.
After a widely criticized election last year, the ruling party and its allies won the last opposition seat and now control 100 percent of the parliament.
At the same time, tensions are rising along the border with Eritrea, where a battle for control of the volatile, controversial line claimed hundreds of lives in June.
Analysts fear that separatists like the Oromo Liberation Front or Ogaden National Liberation Front, who have been more or less defeated in recent years, could take advantage of the turbulence and rearm.
Several factors explain why feelings of bitterness are now exploding beneath the surface after years of hiccuping.
The first one seems harmless: smartphones.
Only in recent years have many Ethiopians been able to communicate through social media as cheaper smartphones became more common and Internet services improved.
Even when the government blocks access to Facebook and Twitter, which it does periodically, especially during protests, many people can still communicate via proxies that hide their whereabouts.
Several young Ethiopians said they gathered to protest.
The second factor is that there is more solidarity between the Oromo and the Amhara, the two largest ethnic groups in Ethiopia.
The Oromos and Amharas are not natural enemies.
For eons, the Amhara, who come from Ethiopia's predominantly Christian highlands, have prospered politically and economically while exploiting the Oromo, many of whom are Muslim and live in lowland areas.
But that's changing, too.
"We are in the process of coordinating under one umbrella", said Mulatu Gemechu, an Oromo leader.
The largest protests took place in Amhara and Oromo areas.
Many Amharas and Oromo feel that Ethiopia is unfairly dominated by members of the Tigray ethnic group, who make up about 6 percent of the population and dominate the military, intelligence, commerce and politics.
The third reason for the unrest is the death of Meles Zenawi.
Mr. Meles, a former rebel leader, served as Ethiopia's prime minister for 17 years until his death in 2012 from an undisclosed illness.
He was considered a tactical genius, a man who could think in corners.
Analysts say he was particularly adept at picking up early signs of dissatisfaction and using special agents to manipulate opponents and render them harmless.
"The current regime lacks this fundamental skill", said Mr Abdi, a conflict analyst.
Ethiopia's new Prime Minister, Hailemariam Desalegn, was chosen for relatively obscure reasons to take the place of Mr Meles.
Unlike Mr Meles, who came from the Tigray region of northern Ethiopia, Mr Hailemariam comes from the south.
Analysts say he does not have the confidence of the Tigray-controlled security services.
Many fear that more bloodshed will result.
The last time Ethiopia experienced such unrest was in 2005, after thousands protested against elections that analysts said were apparently rigged by the government and then stolen.
During the raids that followed, many protesters were killed, although fewer than in the previous months, and the period of unrest passed relatively quickly.
Development experts praised Ethiopia's leaders for their visionary infrastructure planning, such as the new commuter train, and for their measurable progress in poverty alleviation.
But this obviously did not prevent the Ethiopian government's internal discontent from intensifying.
And it takes a dangerous ethnic form.
Last month, protesters attacked Tigray-run businesses in Gondar, an Amharic city, and hatred of the Tigray is becoming more common on social media.
Analysts say the protests are putting the U.S. and other Western allies in a strange position.
The US government used Ethiopia as a base for drone flights over neighboring Somalia, although it recently announced that it had closed that base.
While the West clearly wants to support democracy, it does not want its ally to collapse in an already volatile region.
"This", said Mr. Abdi, "is a very thin line walk".
