Greenland shark: the oldest vertebrate is almost 400 years old
It's a rare sight.
Greenland sharks usually only come to the surface in winter.
This shark was released back into the sea after an examination aboard the research vessel Sanna.
He was born in 1624, and he's swimming across the North Atlantic at a mile an hour -- to this day.
Greenland sharks don't get their young until they're 150 years old.
Slowly, the Greenland shark swims along the bottom of the North Atlantic, averaging just 4,200 feet [1,220 m] in an hour.
When it does, the five-meter- long animal accelerates to a whopping 2.6 km/ hr - half the speed of a seal.
But this slow-motion lifestyle seems to be a recipe for old age.
However, Julius Nielsen of the University of Copenhagen and his colleagues report in the journal Science that a Greenland shark may be 392 years old.
"It's crazy", says Alexander Scheuerlein of the Max Planck Institute for Demographic Research in Rostock, Germany, when he comments on the fact that this is a world record for vertebrates.
It's true that evolutionary biologists have long suspected that Greenland sharks become petrified.
But the evidence was lacking.
Greenland sharks are difficult to spot, since they live mainly in the Arctic Ocean off the sparsely populated coasts of Canada, Greenland, Norway, and Spitsbergen.
Because they prefer water temperatures of about six degrees Celsius, they usually only appear on the surface in winter.
Researchers know correspondingly little about the lifestyle of the Greenland shark.
They measured their time-lapse rate when they equipped six animals with a transmitter in front of Spitzbergen.
But the sharks do prey: In one animal's stomach, researchers found the remains of a seal, and another had swallowed the jawbone of a young polar bear.
They may be hunting dormant animals or patrolling the bottom of the sea of ice, looking for cadavers tumbling down from higher layers of water.
Julius Nielsen and his colleagues studied 28 Greenland sharks that fishermen had taken from the depths of the North Atlantic between 2010 and 2013 as bycatch off Greenland or Spitsbergen.
The smallest shark was just over two feet [81 cm] long, while the largest was over two feet [502 cm].
To determine the age of the animals, they used the carbon-14 method to analyze the shark's lens.
This lens center is formed before the shark is born, and the proteins in it are not renewed later.
The two smallest sharks had a striking amount of carbon-14 in their lens cores.
Their birth should therefore be after the early 1960's, when nuclear weapons tests released greater amounts of this radioactive carbon into the atmosphere.
The third smallest animal, measuring 220 centimetres, had a small excess of carbon-14 from nuclear weapons tests in its lens, so it would have celebrated its 50th birthday in 2012.
All the larger Greenland sharks, on the other hand, had normal levels of carbon-14 in their lens cores, which is produced by cosmic radiation in the atmosphere.
In fact, the carbon-14 clock for a two-foot-long [493 cm] Greenland shark showed an age of 335 years, while the record-breaking shark of two-foot-long [50 cm] may actually be 392 years old.
It was known that Greenland sharks only gave birth to young when they were over four meters long.
Now, researchers could assign an age to length.
Since one of the 392-centimetre-long animals was probably on the verge of sexual maturity and his age was determined at 156, it is obvious that the Greenland shark can reproduce for at least a century and a half.
This too is likely to be the current world record for vertebrates.
It is no coincidence that these species of fish live primarily in icy waters.
The previous record holder, a 211-year-old Greenland whale with a 120-year-old harpoon-tip stuck in its neck, was also caught off Alaska.
The low temperatures often put the organisms of the animals living there on a low.
So they mature later - and age more slowly.
To keep warm in the cold water, the animals also often grow extra large.
Because the volume grows much faster than its surface, through which the animal loses heat.
The heat loss of a gram mouse is therefore much greater than that of a gram elephant.
Another advantage is that you have fewer enemies.
"So a smaller animal is more dangerous and should focus on having as many offspring as possible as soon as possible", explains evolutionary biologist Scheuerlein.
A very large animal, on the other hand, should invest its resources in a long life.
