The price was quite high: 2700 D-Mark, or about 1,400 euros.
The average sales price of a smartphone in Germany in 2015 was 392 euros.
No one could have predicted in August 1996 that the Communicator would be the beginning of the smartphone era.
Everything has changed since then.
Smart phones are a success story, though not for Nokia.
The Finnish mobile phone division suffered an unprecedented disaster, was eventually sold to Microsoft and wound up.
The market today is dominated by vendors, all of whom came much later than Nokia.
Being online all the time and everywhere is a fact of life for many people today.
In 2015, there were nearly two billion smartphone users worldwide.
Some 1.4 billion devices have been sold, of which 555 million are Samsung and Apple alone.
The worldwide turnover of these devices is about 400 billion euros.
In addition, there are the thriving businesses of countless app providers and telecommunications companies.
A whole industry has developed around the smartphone.
The decisive breakthrough to the mass market came in early 2007, when Apple CEO Steve Jobs announced the launch of the iPhone at Mac World.
He promised three devices in one: a music player, a telephone and an Internet communicator, all easily operated by a touch screen.
Apple's triumph began, and to this day, the iPhone is the company's most important product.
Nokia, Motorola and Blackberry, who dominated the market, had the upper hand.
They disappeared, Blackberry has to fight.
Apple and Asian vendors like Samsung are now in charge.
The smartphone is a given 20 years after its invention.
On average, every German now checks his or her mobile phone 88 times a day.
"We all have to learn to put away our smartphones", said Janina Kugel, who is responsible for human resources on the Siemens board.
Permanent accessibility is now considered both a curse and a blessing.
