Venus was once habitable
Venus was probably habitable at one time, according to projections from a new NASA climate model.
Scientists at NASA's Goddard Institute for Space Studies have developed a model to discover the past of Venus using tools and algorithms similar to those used by climate scientists.
The model was designed to determine whether Venus, with its hot, waterless surface and CO2-dense atmosphere, may have once had conditions similar to Earth's.
Scientists have previously suggested that Venus's slow rotation could be explained by its dense atmosphere.
But the latest simulation suggests that Venus may have had a thin, Earth-like atmosphere and still slowly rotated away.
The model also illuminated the topography of early Venus.
The planet probably had more arid areas than Earth, but once had enough water and geographic variability to support life and protect it from rapid evaporation.
Early Venus also benefited from a sun that was 30 percent matter.
"In the GISS model simulation, Venus's slow rotation exposes its day side to the sun for almost two months", explained GISS scientist Anthony Del Genio in a press release.
This heats the surface and produces rain, which creates a thick layer of clouds that acts like an umbrella to shield the surface from much of the sun's heat.
The result is average temperatures that are a few degrees cooler than those on Earth today.
The model produced a story of Venus that resembles the evolution that planetary scientists had previously suspected.
Although it was once thought to be habitable, Venus has been exposed to too much heat and ultraviolet light over billions of years.
Their oceans evaporated, and their water vapor was burned away by ultraviolet light.
When their hydrogen ran out, all that was left was a thick atmosphere of carbon dioxide with a deadly greenhouse effect -- the Venus we know today.
The researchers shared the results of their new Venus climate model in the Geophysical Research Letters.
