Data theft: How hackers blackmail their victims to collect ransom
Extortion malware programmers are now targeting businesses - and they're succeeding.
According to a recent survey of 540 companies in North America, the United Kingdom and Germany by malware-prevention specialist Malwarebytes, 40 percent of the companies surveyed had been the victim of at least one, sometimes multiple, ransomware attack in the past 12 months.
In Germany, almost 20 percent of companies have been the target of ransomware extortion.
Forty percent of victims willingly paid the ransom demanded by the attackers in order to regain access to the systems and data that were attacked.
The perpetrators are increasingly specializing their extortion software in attacks on corporate networks, according to the observations of Malwarebytes.
If they succeed, the potential ransom to be extorted is much higher than for private users.
"We are seeing a frighteningly rapid evolution of malware", says Malwarebytes' CEO Marcin Kleczynski in an interview with Die Welt.
In 2008, most malware was designed to send out ads.
Then the perpetrators discovered blackmail software for themselves.
At first, private users were targeted, but the shift to corporate attacks has been occurring at an alarmingly rapid rate in recent months.
Ransomware works in a simple pattern: Once active on a victim's computer, it searches for files that have been recently modified, such as Word, Excel, or database files, as well as archives of images and videos.
These files are encrypted by the ransomware and the originals are permanently erased.
The software then presents the demands of the blackmailers.
To get the end-to-end encryption code to the files, the victims have to wire money -- usually in the form of the cryptocurrency Bitcoin.
However, where the personal photo database is at stake for private users, it is sensitive customer data or project databases that are at stake for companies, without which production stands still.
So, the damage is higher when a ransomware attacks.
22 percent of affected German companies reported revenue losses due to ransomware, 13 percent even had to completely stop business, in one case people's lives were in danger.
In Germany, hospitals have already been the victims of attacks, which may put patients at acute risk of losing medical records.
"We always tell victims: 'Don't pay, you are only adding to the problem,'" Kleczynski explains.
But 80 to 90 percent of the companies that pay, they get their data back.
It is difficult for managers to refuse the demand of the perpetrators in the face of a standstill in the operation.
Hackers know this and they'll do anything to build a good reputation.
In a recent study, F-Secure security researchers have examined the user interfaces and the interaction with the blackmailers and come to the conclusion that the offenders are actually trying to build a kind of customer service to make more money.
They chat with their victims, explain how to pay with bitcoin, set up free support websites, or decrypt sample files for free.
And when private individuals are ransomed for a few hundred euros, companies sometimes have to negotiate hard and pay five-figure sums to get their data back unencrypted.
Given the high potential and relatively riskless returns from ransomware extortion, hackers are becoming more professional and sharing the work, explains security expert Chester Wisniewski of antivirus company Sophos: "A single person can write a ransomware in about a week".
But it is more likely that it is three or four people.
The programmers then sell their malware in the form of a software build to the actual ransomware.
The malware kits that we've seen so far have been created by buying the malware itself, advice and additional tools for a one-time, flat-rate price of between $1,000 and $10,000.
"The package includes an adaptation tool, so that smaller configurations, appearance and branding can be changed", says Wisniewski.
The blackmailers then seek out more hackers to distribute the newly purchased software to the victims.
We live in a service economy.
So you log into one of the underground forums, buy the set from one criminal, and then commission another to install the software on as many PCs as possible.
Payment is made per infected computer.
"Usually, criminals then commission spammers to distribute it", explains Wisniewski.
The risk of ransomware is now known to many companies that have become better at securing their data.
Over 50 percent of the IT executives surveyed by Malwarebytes believe that they can defend against ransomware by using file backup and scanning software.
Accordingly, the perpetrators are already pursuing new strategies.
"If encrypting data is not enough to threaten successful seizure, the perpetrators are threatening to release sensitive data such as customer lists or price calculations", explains Malwarebytes CEO Marcin Kleczynski.
This means that the potential for damage is many times greater than before, depending on the type of data.
The Internet of Things could also be a new target for criminals.
At the Defcon hacker conference, security researchers demonstrated how they could take control of a thermostat connected to the Internet.
In the middle of winter, the unlocking of such a blocked heater may well be worth a ransom to some victims.
So if, in the future, instead of heating, the perpetrators block an entire production line in a factory, ransomware could also become an issue in Industry 4.0.
